When John Prentice Powell bought a ruined colonial house in the capital of Yucatán, the city's heyday had long past but his knowledge of the historic architecture saw him become the suavest of estate agents. Text: Kevin Guyer, Photography: Don Freeman.
Pick up a December issue, https://t.co/aKl9oIJqG8
@theworldofinteriors December issue is our 40th anniversary special, celebrating four decades of the world's most influential design and decoration magazine. https://t.co/TizSH6F0Xa

Reputedly 'the naughtiest woman in France' Fortunée Hamelin fancied herself a bit of an interiors maven and tastemaker, decorating her Paris home in full Directoire fashion. Text: Philippe Seuillet. Photography Guillaume de Laubier. Pick up a November issue of for the full story. https://t.co/YayOyhmIjM

Having waited to get her hands on this particular holiday home in Menorca, a delighted Paloma Cañizares was eager to finally make her mark on it. Feature by Muriel Zagha, photography by Ricardo Labougle.
Pick up an October issue of for the full story. https://t.co/5uuHUFc8XY

Artist Edmund Fairfax-Lucy regarded his paintings as an ongoing process - 'records of the time of their creation', rarely completed - and brought the same evolutionary approach to bear on his Warwickshire ancestral home, Charlecote Park. 📷 Antony Crolla. Pick up an October issue https://t.co/74JkCQUDaK

@CondeNast today named @hamishbowles as the new editor in chief at The World of Interiors. In his expanded role, Bowles will lead The World of Interiors’ editorial team into a new era that honours the magazine’s timeless heritage, known for celebrating the unique and the unusual. https://t.co/hLxAaGB1Fl

Be it periodicals, toys or bicycle paraphernalia, Sir Paul Smith is an incorrigible collector of stuff. While some ends up in his boutiques, less can be found cluttering up the fashion designer's tranquil London home.  Photos by Simon Upton. Pick up a September issue. https://t.co/lS7gRiwVjw

@WofInteriors September issue is out on July 29th, the cover story features the ornate Bolognese palazzo of textile designer Idarica Gazzoni, where the great Rossini once lived. 
Cosmo Brockway leads the applause. Photography by James McDonald. https://t.co/cFr75ajmzP

For a century and more, Maverick Concert Hall near Woodstock, has delighted chamber musicians with its ear-seducing acoustics. Now, after a major renovation, 'music in the woods' is about to fill the glade once more. Photography Don Freeman. 
Pick up an August issue. https://t.co/5HPgo5lpvB

Art dealer William Thuillier specialises in 'sleepers', typically old-master paintings whose attribution is uncertain. Many of them are on display in the grand Regency-flat-cum-gallery he shares with  Alvaro Picardo. Text and photography James McDonald.  Pick up an August issue. https://t.co/oSnzMph15R

@Dreweatts_1759 sale: A Lifetime's Passion: Property from The Fell Collection comprises sculpture, Chinese porcelain, silverware and antique furniture. The collection has been styled by interior decorator Charles Benjamin of Acroterium and takes place on 21 July. https://t.co/oDhSXaCmKB

In the 1780s a feckless son gambled away his inheritance, Villa Silvio Pellico. Some 230 years later, presented with a high-stakes deadline to buy the  Neoclassical gem, the would-be owners decided to capitalise on a good deal. Photography Simon Upton. Pick up an August issue. https://t.co/h8I2UwVQI1

@ronaldvanderhilst is an expert in historic tulips, the kind that drove the 17th-century Dutch republic into a frenzy of speculation. He has created a hortus conclusus in a presbytery plot - one a stone's throw from his bohemian home in Antwerp. 
Photography @renestoeltie. https://t.co/mQCRe7K59E

Ferdinand IV was a man of such callow pursuits that he turned a tumbledown tower at his Bourbon palace, Reggia di Caserta, into a pretend fort so he could indulge in his favourite pastime - playing soldiers. Photography Ricardo Labougle.  Pick up a July issue for the full story. https://t.co/VNKdK6seK8

The impact of the Black Death from 1347 to 1351 killed an estimated 30-50% of the European population and had a massive impact on the psyche of the Middle Ages. Jewellery that showed the very real impact of mortality manifested in ‘memento mori’ (remember you will die) symbol

By the late 17th century, following the Restoration of the Crown, memento mori symbols became completely appropriated in mourning jewellery. Having the skull and crossbones set within crystal containing a lock of hair became the standard for future mourning jewels. https://t.co/JX68GZzNOg
